Ensure tokens do not contain invalid UTF-8 bytes

**Why**: If someone sends a request with an Ahoy Cookie or Header that
contains an invalid UTF-8 byte, the app will raise
`ArgumentError: invalid byte sequence in UTF-8`.

**How**:  Encode the token as UTF-8, and replace any invalid or
undefined bytes with an empty string.

Rails tracker example: store more useful info (#318)

`controller_path` also stores the controller's namespace, where `controller_name` wouldn't. So for example `controller_path` would return `admin/users#show` while `controller_name` would return `users#show`.

`request.path_parameters` are any params that Rails parsed in order to route the request, e.g. in the above example it'd include the user ID

Test Ahoy.geocode

Test that setting Ahoy.geocode to false removes the three
location-specific keys from the VisitProperties hash.

Prior to this commit there were no tests, so this commit introduces a
simple test harness using Minitest (as per
https://github.com/ankane/searchkick/). Since this gem is designed to be
used inside a Rails application it makes use of methods that only rails
provides (notably for this commit VisitProperties uses `delegate` from
active_support). This meant I had to introduce rails as a development
dependency in order for the tests to run.

Make Ahoy.geocode apply everywhere

In 729d9e4496b3875 the ability to disable geocoding was introduced. It
only applied to those stores that callsed `set_visit_properties`, which
the LogStore, for example, does not.

This commit moves the removal of the LOCATION_KEYS from VisitProperties
into the VisitProperties class, so that it will apply everywhere.
